posts.name: Keith Farelle Cozart
posts.cooked:
What type of flat belt/webbing do teams normally use for elevators? (1114 and 2056 in 2018/2019). I’m looking at McMaster-Carr , and I’m also curious about how Belt compares to Dyneema in terms of creep / constructional elongation. Any help would be great! image 452×679 54.3 KB

image 452×679 54.3 KB

image 452×679 54.3 KB

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked:
Belts are normally fiber reinforced and really don’t creep/stretch at all.  Jump a tooth or three… yes.  Braided line has some kind of “settling in” mechanism that causes some initial lengthening that stabilizes.  Some vendors sell it “pre-stretched”.

The 3D printer market means that spools of belt that match your pulley of choice are readily available.

posts.name: Vaughn Khouri
posts.cooked:
For belt driven elevators, the gold standard the last year or two has been this HTD5 18mm Wide Kevlar Backed Timing Belt , stocked by WCP . It was used to drive the vertical elevator on 1323 2023 robot and also in 4414s 2023 elevator; both were rigged continuous, but 1323’s only had a single stage.

This is probably overkill, and you’ll only use a fraction of the 25’ roll, but if you’re going to build a belt driven elevator (especially with the rigging inside the tubes) it’s worth it in my opinion because if you snap / strip the belt, it reallllllly blows to re rig it at competition.

Even though belt does not stretch as much as something like UHW or Dyneema, you’ll still want to have a good tensioner on each terminating end. I really like HighTide’s one, which integrates a cam tensioner into a sliding clamp .

The use of flat webbing for the loop in a cascading elevator isn’t worth it in my opinion; it’s much harder to tension. I’d highly recommend using UHWMPE cord and tensioning it with a ratchet block like shown here , unless you have some kind of special case. We’ve climbed off this kind of rigging with 0 issues many times this year.

posts.name: Brandon Holley
posts.cooked:
Our 2018 elevator used a continuous 25mm wide HTD belt (5mm pitch).

The “carriage” of the elevator was a mostly 3d printed assembly that had a clamping block integrated as well as the end of a 1/2" ratcheting wrench.  The belt was clamped on one side, fed through the entire system (including the drive pulley in the gearbox) and then wrapped around the hex shaft and tightened until the system was nice and tight.

We’ve used this same style system now with great success in several other designs (our 2019 arm, our 2023 arm, several FTC robots).

You can see the details here: Onshape

-Brando

We used this 15mm wide, 5M HTD Kevlar-backed sourced from Polybelt last year on our 2 stage continuous elevator. I can’t speak to long-term reliability without being tensioned, as we were forced to tension a lot due to a few unrelated failures causing teeth to skip. If you intend to do a similar continuous-rigged elevator with this style of belt I’d HIGHLY recommend a robust tensioning system, something at the level of 4414 HighTide’s 2023 solution.
